<?php
$studyOptions = array("a" => "Observational study", "b" => "Experiment");
$claimOptions = array("a" => "Association only", "b" => "Cause and effect is supported", "c" => "Neither conclusion is supported");

return array(
    "overview" => "Observational studies measure what people already do, while experiments deliberately impose treatments. That single difference controls whether a result can show association or provide evidence of causation.",
    "objectives" => array(
        "Classify a study by asking whether researchers assigned a treatment.",
        "Distinguish association from causation.",
        "Identify explanatory, response, lurking, and confounding variables.",
        "Distinguish random selection from random assignment and evaluate generalization separately from causation.",
        "Compare retrospective and prospective observational designs and rewrite overclaimed conclusions."
    ),
    "prerequisites" => array("Identify explanatory and response variables.", "Recognize random sampling and basic sources of bias.", "Understand that two variables can change together."),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Observational study", "A study that measures variables without deliberately assigning treatments."),
        array("Experiment", "A study that deliberately imposes one or more treatments and measures a response."),
        array("Treatment", "A condition deliberately applied to an experimental unit."),
        array("Association", "A relationship in which knowing one variable gives information about another."),
        array("Causation", "A relationship in which changing one variable directly produces a change in another."),
        array("Confounding variable", "A variable related to both the explanatory and response variables whose effect cannot be separated."),
        array("Lurking variable", "An unmeasured or omitted variable that may help explain an observed relationship."),
        array("Retrospective study", "An observational study that looks backward through records or memories."),
        array("Prospective study", "An observational study that follows participants forward through time."),
        array("Generalization", "Extending a study result from the participants to a wider population.")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "The Assignment Test", "content" => array(
            "<p>The fastest way to classify a study is to ask: <strong>Did the researchers deliberately assign an explanatory condition?</strong> In an observational study, researchers watch, ask, or use records. Students may already choose to study at night, customers may already use different subscription plans, and patients may already have different exposures. The researchers measure those existing differences without imposing them.</p>",
            "<p>In an experiment, researchers deliberately apply a treatment. They might assign students to one of two study apps, show users different website layouts, or set plants under different light conditions. An experiment does not have to occur in a laboratory, use a placebo, or involve medicine. A field test on school websites is still an experiment if the research team assigns the versions.</p>",
            array("type" => "warning", "label" => "Before-and-after is not enough", "html" => "<p>Measuring participants before and after a naturally occurring event does not automatically create an experiment. There must be an imposed treatment. Likewise, merely asking whether someone used a product does not assign product use.</p>"),
            "<p>The assignment test is more reliable than keywords such as compare, group, control, or study. An observational report can compare groups, and an experiment can be conducted in ordinary settings. State who imposed the condition and what it was. If participants chose their own exposure, the design remains observational.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Association Is Not Automatically Causation", "content" => array(
            "<p>Two variables are <strong>associated</strong> when values of one tend to occur with particular values of the other. Students who report more sleep may also report higher grades. That pattern may be real and useful for prediction, but it does not prove that forcing more sleep would raise grades. An association can arise from causation, reverse causation, common causes, selection effects, or chance.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Causation</strong> claims that changing the explanatory variable directly changes the response. Randomized experiments provide the strongest evidence because random assignment tends to balance other characteristics across treatments. If treatment groups begin comparably and are treated alike except for the assigned condition, a later response difference has fewer alternative explanations.</p>",
            "<p>Even a dramatic observational association does not erase alternatives. Ice-cream sales and sunburns both rise in summer, but ice cream does not cause sunburn. Warm sunny weather affects both. Likewise, social-media use and stress may be related, but stress might change use, use might change stress, or sleep, workload, and social support may affect both.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "Cautious language", "html" => "<p>For observational evidence, use phrases such as \"is associated with,\" \"is related to,\" or \"predicts in this sample.\" Reserve \"causes,\" \"leads to,\" and \"results in\" for designs that justify causal inference.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Confounding and Lurking Variables", "content" => array(
            "<p>A <strong>confounding variable</strong> is connected to both the explanatory and response variables, so its effect overlaps with the relationship being studied. Suppose tutoring participants earn higher grades. Motivation may be confounding: motivated students may seek tutoring and may also complete more practice, attend class, and earn higher grades for reasons beyond tutoring.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>lurking variable</strong> is relevant but omitted from the analysis. Textbooks vary slightly in how they separate lurking and confounding. A practical distinction is that a lurking variable is not measured, while a confounder is an alternative influence entangled with the explanatory variable. Either way, name a plausible variable and explain both links. Writing \"motivation\" alone is incomplete.</p>",
            "<p>Good confounders are not simply anything that might affect the response. In a study of screen time and sleep, room temperature might affect sleep but may have no connection to screen time. It is an outside source of variation, not necessarily a confounder. Homework load could be a confounder if heavier workloads increase evening screen use and reduce sleep.</p>",
            array("type" => "example", "label" => "Two-link test", "html" => "<p>For any proposed confounder C, complete both sentences: \"C may influence the explanatory variable because...\" and \"C may influence the response because...\" If one link is missing, reconsider.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Generalization and Causation Are Separate", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Random selection</strong> and <strong>random assignment</strong> answer different questions. Random selection from a clearly defined population makes the participants more representative, supporting generalization to that population. Random assignment places experimental units into treatments, reducing confounding and supporting causal comparison among units similar to those studied.</p>",
            "<p>An experiment with volunteers and random assignment can support a causal claim for people similar to the volunteers but may not generalize to every student. An observational study with an excellent random sample may generalize an association to a population but still cannot establish causation. A study that uses both random selection and random assignment has the strongest combination, although practical studies rarely achieve perfection.</p>",
            "<table><thead><tr><th>Design feature</th><th>Main support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Random selection</td><td>Generalizing from sample to population</td></tr><tr><td>Random assignment</td><td>Comparing treatments for cause and effect</td></tr><tr><td>Neither</td><td>Results may still describe participants, but wider claims need caution</td></tr></tbody></table>",
            "<p>Always identify the target population before generalizing. A randomized experiment conducted with adult volunteers cannot automatically describe children. Causation and scope are two different dimensions of a conclusion.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Why Observational Studies Remain Essential", "content" => array(
            "<p>Some treatments cannot be assigned ethically or practically. Researchers cannot assign people to smoke, experience dangerous pollution, have a particular age, or suffer an injury. Observational studies are also useful for rare outcomes, long-term patterns, and events that have already occurred. They can reveal important associations and guide later research.</p>",
            "<p>A <strong>retrospective</strong> study looks backward using medical records, archived grades, purchase histories, or memories. It can be efficient but may face incomplete records and recall bias. A <strong>prospective</strong> study records current characteristics and follows participants forward, which improves measurement planning but takes time and can lose participants.</p>",
            "<p>Researchers strengthen observational evidence by measuring possible confounders, comparing similar groups, using repeated studies, checking dose-response patterns, and asking whether the timing and mechanism make sense. These strategies do not turn observation into random assignment, but they help evaluate competing explanations. Honest conclusions state both the association found and the design limitation.</p>"
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Coffee and test scores", "scenario" => "Researchers compare students who choose to drink coffee before a test with students who do not.", "steps" => array("No one is assigned to drink coffee, so this is observational.", "Coffee choice is explanatory and test score is the response.", "Sleep, prior achievement, stress, and study time may be connected to both coffee use and scores.", "The design can describe an association but cannot isolate a causal coffee effect."), "conclusion" => "Use association language, not 'coffee caused the score difference.'"),
        array("title" => "Assigned study applications", "scenario" => "Two hundred students are randomly assigned to App A or App B for four weeks, then take the same assessment.", "steps" => array("The research team imposes the app, so this is an experiment.", "Random assignment tends to balance prior achievement and motivation.", "The assigned app is the treatment; assessment score is the response.", "If procedures are otherwise controlled, a score difference supports a causal conclusion for students similar to those studied."), "conclusion" => "Random assignment, not the presence of two apps, provides causal leverage."),
        array("title" => "Exercise and stress records", "scenario" => "A random sample of students reports exercise frequency and current stress.", "steps" => array("Exercise was measured rather than assigned, so the study is observational.", "The random sample can support generalizing the observed association to the represented student population.", "Workload, sleep, and health may confound the relationship.", "A suitable conclusion is that exercise frequency and reported stress were associated."), "conclusion" => "Random sampling helps scope, but it does not convert association into causation."),
        array("title" => "Historical purchase study", "scenario" => "A company uses last year's purchase records to compare retention across existing subscription plans.", "steps" => array("Plans were already chosen, making the study observational.", "Looking backward through records makes it retrospective.", "Income, product need, and prior loyalty may affect both plan choice and retention.", "The result can guide hypotheses but should not claim the plan caused retention."), "conclusion" => "Existing records reveal patterns while leaving selection and confounding concerns."),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("Any study involving people is observational.", "People can be experimental units when researchers assign treatments ethically."),
        array("Before-and-after measurement creates an experiment.", "The design is experimental only when researchers impose a treatment."),
        array("A strong association proves causation.", "Strength does not eliminate confounding, reverse direction, or selection effects."),
        array("Random selection and assignment are interchangeable.", "Selection supports generalization; assignment supports causal comparison."),
        array("Observational studies are useless.", "They are essential when assignment is unethical or impossible and can produce valuable predictive and descriptive evidence."),
        array("Experiments must occur in laboratories.", "Field experiments, classroom trials, and website A/B tests can all impose treatments.")
    ),
    "why" => array(
        "Causal language affects decisions. A school may buy a program, a company may redesign a product, or a person may change behaviour based on a claim. Knowing what the design actually supports prevents an association from being sold as a guaranteed effect.",
        "The assignment test, two-link confounder explanation, and separation of causation from generalization form a reliable checklist for reading research in news reports and academic summaries."
    ),
    "knowledge_check" => array(
        stats_classify("kc1", "Researchers record existing sleep habits and grades without assigning sleep schedules.", $studyOptions, "a", "<p>No treatment is imposed, so this is observational.</p>", "Who chose the sleep schedule?", "foundational", array("study type")),
        stats_classify("kc2", "A website randomly shows visitors one of two button designs and records clicks.", $studyOptions, "b", "<p>The website assigns a design, making this an experiment.</p>", "A condition is imposed.", "foundational", array("study type")),
        stats_classify("kc3", "A representative survey finds students who sleep longer have higher grades. What conclusion is directly supported?", $claimOptions, "a", "<p>The observational survey supports an association, not causation.</p>", "Representative does not mean treatment was assigned.", "foundational", array("causation"))
    ),
    "guided_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("g1", "A coach records athletes' chosen shoe brands and injury rates.", $studyOptions, "a", "<p>Shoe brand is chosen by athletes, so this is observational.</p>", "Was footwear assigned?", "foundational", array("study type")),
        stats_classify("g2", "A coach randomly assigns two warm-up routines and compares sprint times.", $studyOptions, "b", "<p>The coach imposes routines, so this is an experiment.</p>", "Assigned routine means treatment.", "foundational", array("study type")),
        stats_written("g3", "short-response", "In a study of tutoring attendance and grades, explain how motivation may confound the relationship.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> More motivated students may be more likely to attend tutoring and may also study more or complete more work, independently raising grades. The effects of motivation and tutoring are difficult to separate.</p>", "Show both links to motivation.", "proficient", array("confounding")),
        stats_classify("g4", "A random sample is observed, with no treatment assignment. Which claim level is strongest?", $claimOptions, "a", "<p>Random sampling supports population generalization of an association, but no assignment means no direct causal claim.</p>", "Selection and assignment are different.", "proficient", array("scope", "causation")),
        stats_written("g5", "short-response", "Rewrite: 'Students who use planners earn higher marks, so planners cause better grades.'", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Students who used planners had higher marks in this study. Planner use was associated with marks, but motivation, organization, and workload may explain part of the difference.</p>", "Replace causal words and name an alternative.", "proficient", array("conclusion")),
        stats_written("g6", "short-response", "Give one ethical reason an observational study would be required.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Researchers cannot assign participants to a harmful exposure such as smoking or unsafe pollution, so they must observe naturally occurring exposure while protecting participants.</p>", "Think of a treatment no researcher should impose.", "foundational", array("ethics")),
        stats_written("g7", "short-response", "Distinguish retrospective from prospective studies.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Retrospective studies look backward using past records or memories. Prospective studies record current information and follow participants forward to observe later outcomes.</p>", "Past records versus future follow-up.", "foundational", array("observational designs")),
        stats_written("g8", "error-analysis", "A student says random assignment makes the participants representative of all teenagers. Correct the error.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Random assignment balances treatment groups among the participants. Representativeness requires random selection from the target population; assignment does not change how participants entered.</p>", "Separate entry from placement.", "advanced", array("assignment", "generalization"))
    ),
    "independent_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("i1", "Researchers compare medical records of people with and without a past exposure.", $studyOptions, "a", "<p>Past exposure was not assigned, so this is a retrospective observational study.</p>", "Existing records indicate observation.", "foundational", array("study type")),
        stats_classify("i2", "Classrooms are randomly assigned to two teaching schedules.", $studyOptions, "b", "<p>The schedule is imposed on classrooms, which are the experimental units.</p>", "Groups can be experimental units.", "proficient", array("study type")),
        stats_classify("i3", "A randomized experiment finds a difference between treatments. Which claim is supported if procedures were controlled?", $claimOptions, "b", "<p>Random assignment and controlled treatment comparison support a cause-and-effect conclusion for similar units.</p>", "Look for random assignment.", "proficient", array("causation")),
        stats_written("i4", "short-response", "Propose a confounder for the association between social-media time and sleep duration, and explain both links.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Homework load may increase late-night device use for communication or schoolwork and may independently reduce available sleep time. Other two-link explanations are acceptable.</p>", "Name why it affects each main variable.", "proficient", array("confounding")),
        stats_written("i5", "short-response", "Can a carefully designed observational study ever support useful conclusions? Explain.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Yes. It can estimate population characteristics, identify and quantify associations, study harmful or fixed exposures, and guide later research. Its conclusion should acknowledge that unmeasured confounding limits direct causal inference.</p>", "Useful does not have to mean causal.", "proficient", array("observational value")),
        stats_written("i6", "short-response", "A study randomly selects users and randomly assigns two notification systems. State what each random step supports.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Random selection supports generalizing results to the represented user population. Random assignment supports interpreting response differences as effects of the notification system.</p>", "One step concerns scope; the other concerns cause.", "advanced", array("selection", "assignment")),
        stats_written("i7", "error-analysis", "A report says a 0.92 correlation proves that one variable causes the other. Explain the error.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Correlation strength measures association, not design quality. A confounder, reverse causation, or selection process can produce a strong relationship without direct causation.</p>", "A number cannot replace random assignment.", "advanced", array("causation")),
        stats_written("i8", "short-response", "Write an appropriate conclusion for an observational study finding exercise and stress are negatively associated.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> In the studied group, students who reported more frequent exercise tended to report lower stress. The design shows association and does not by itself prove that increasing exercise would cause stress to fall.</p>", "Include context and a limitation.", "proficient", array("conclusion")),
        stats_written("i9", "short-response", "Explain one advantage and one weakness of a retrospective study.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> It can examine long periods quickly using existing records, but records may be incomplete and memories inaccurate, and potential confounders may not have been measured.</p>", "Efficiency versus data quality.", "proficient", array("retrospective")),
        stats_written("i10", "short-response", "Analyse a study in which volunteers choose a diet, are followed for a year, and have health outcomes measured. Identify design, variables, confounding, and claim limit.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> This is a prospective observational study because diet is chosen, not assigned. Diet is explanatory and the health measure is the response. Income, prior health, exercise, and motivation may confound. The study can report association among volunteers but cannot isolate a causal diet effect or automatically generalize to everyone.</p>", "Use the assignment, confounder, and scope checks.", "advanced", array("full analysis"))
    ),
    "summary" => array(
        "Observational studies measure existing conditions; experiments impose treatments.",
        "Association describes a pattern, while causation claims a direct effect.",
        "A confounder must plausibly connect to both the explanatory and response variables.",
        "Random selection supports generalization; random assignment supports causation.",
        "Retrospective and prospective studies remain valuable when experiments are unethical or impractical."
    ),
    "exit_ticket" => array(
        stats_classify("e1", "A school assigns half of participating classes to a new schedule by coin flip.", $studyOptions, "b", "<p>The assigned schedule is an imposed treatment, so the study is an experiment.</p>", "A coin flip assigns a condition.", "proficient", array("study type")),
        stats_written("e2", "short-response", "Write one sentence explaining why observational association does not establish causation.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Without random assignment, differences in other variables or reverse direction may explain the observed relationship, so the direct effect cannot be isolated.</p>", "Mention an alternative explanation.", "proficient", array("causation"))
    )
);
